## Today's AI Nugget — May 4, 2026

**OptimusKG — FutureHouse and Zitnik Drop a 21-Million-Edge Multimodal Biomedical Knowledge Graph, and Validate It With a Paper-Reading Agent**

OptimusKG, posted to arXiv on April 29 by Lucas Vittor, Ayush Noori, Iñaki Arango, Joaquín Polonuer, Sam Rodriques, Andrew White, David Clifton, and Marinka Zitnik — that author list pulls together FutureHouse, the Zitnik lab at Harvard, and Clifton at Oxford. 190,531 nodes / 21.8M edges / 67M property instances drawn from 18 ontologies, ~5x bigger than PrimeKG, and the load-bearing design choice is the labeled-property-graph (LPG) framing rather than RDF triples — schema enforced at the top level but type-specific properties, cross-references, and provenance kept on edges and nodes themselves. The validation lands hardest for this audience: the team used PaperQA3 (FutureHouse's literature-grounded multimodal agent) to check edges against the published literature — 70.0% of sampled real edges were supported, 83.4% of synthetic false edges were correctly rejected, and the unsupported real edges concentrated in experimental and functional-genomics resources, suggesting the graph captures knowledge that may precede synthesis in the secondary literature. This is the explicit operational pairing the week's through-line has been pointing at: curated, schema-constrained biomedical infrastructure plus an LLM agent that reads papers, in the same pipeline. Paper: https://arxiv.org/abs/2604.27269

