## Today's AI Nugget — 2026-05-12

**AssayBench: An Assay-Level Virtual Cell Benchmark for LLMs and Agents** (arXiv 2605.10876, posted 2026-05-11)

A Genentech-led collaboration assembles 1,920 publicly available CRISPR screens across five broad phenotype classes, formulates phenotypic-screen prediction as gene-rank prediction with an adjusted nDCG metric, and lands a counterintuitive headline: zero-shot generalist frontier LLMs beat biology-specific LLMs and trainable baselines. Third or fourth time this pattern has surfaced this year on a serious biomedical benchmark — at some point it stops being a fluke. Actionable corollary: for biomedical agents that rank perturbations/candidates, lean on prompt optimization, fine-tuning, and ensembling rather than a biology-specific backbone. Two caveats: still far from the empirical noise ceiling, and gene-rank-per-screen is one task in the virtual-cell vision, not the whole vision.

Episode: 4:56 (296s), 2.08 MB at `episodes/2026-05-12-assaybench-generalist-llms-virtual-cell-screen.mp3`. Audio published to R2. Feed updated. Commit `b9f533d` pushed to `main`.

